title: Prologue: Ayanokouji Atsuomi's Monologue
content:
Prologue:
Ayanokouji Atsuomi's Monologue

RICH, POOR—THE DISPARITY of wealth.

Highly educated, poorly educated—the disparity of education.

Urban, rural—the disparity of regions.

Disadvantaged youth, privileged elderly—the disparity of generations.

This Japan is a society of disparities.

The examples I just mentioned are only a small part, but indeed, they represent heaven and hell.

What's important is that many of these circumstances are by no means unchangeable. Just like how a poor person can rise to wealth, a wealthy person can sometimes fall into poverty.

If you disliked regional disparities, you could move to the city.

While I understood that principle, I possessed nothing.

I was born in the countryside, extremely poor, and so uneducated it was pitiful.

I had average physical strength, and I was neither blessed with endurance nor was I a hard worker.

If I had to mention one element I could fight with, it could be my youth.

However, without making use of even that, I spent much of my life wastefully.

It was truly a life spent crawling in the depths of hardship.

There was no bright future waiting for me, and it was possible that I would just lead a miserable life.

However, I carved out my future with my own hands.

There was one thing I had more than others; that was why.

It was an indefinitely expanding 'ambition'—one that couldn’t be suppressed.

I will definitely rise and stand at the pinnacle of this country.

With that alone in my heart, I continued to live till this day.

That ambition was the only support I had in my life.

At twenty-five, I gained my first right to be elected.

Working multiple part-time jobs, I had saved three million yen in deposits.

With this, I would become a politician, a member of the Diet[1], and build a vast amount of fame and fortune.

It was a fleeting, foolish dream. I underestimated the election and was miserably defeated.

It would’ve been better if that was all there was to it, but I didn't even reach the required number of votes, and the three million yen that I had collected with everything on the line was confiscated.

Solving poverty, cleaning politics, finding measures against declining birth rates, improving wages, and advocating for the 'no war' clause.

I thought that if I touted these beautiful ideals indiscriminately, winning the election wouldn’t be difficult. It was a naive and foolish thought.

Such shallow wisdom was something anyone could think of and anyone could realize.

What was important in winning an election was which organization you belonged to and whom you followed.

It was about whether one could discern friend from foe and go along with those in power.

What happened after that? Did you think I fell into ruin?

I requested to join the ruling 'Citizens' Party' and began my steps as a politician.

Yes, two years later, I ran for election again and proved that I could win.

In two years’ time, I succeeded in reaching a position where I could devote myself—all of my efforts—to the world of politics.

I might’ve become one of the winners, but… winning the election wasn’t my goal.

Above all, the world of politics wasn’t so sweet.

No, in a sense, calling it ‘the deepest and darkest world’ might not be an exaggeration. No matter how much ambition I had, I was just one of the inexperienced Diet members without any backing or power.

Most people capable of rising were second- or third-generation politicians who were given rights from the moment they were born.

Sons of ignorant and foolish big-shot politicians kept repeating nonsense as uninspiring as flat soda on TV every night.

Sometimes, there were people who transitioned from the entertainment industry to politics, carrying only their face and popularity.

Most were nothing more than publicity-generating attractions, but they still held more potential than a 'have-not' politician like me. It was an ironic story.

The methods for someone like me to make a name as a politician… those options were limited from the start.

I took on the dirty backroom jobs that nobody wanted to do.

It was a role where, if you failed, your political career would immediately be over. Depending on the situation, you might even face criminal charges.

By willingly taking on these roles, I gradually strengthened my presence within the party.

Eventually, as a secret blade for 'Naoe-sensei,' who controlled many factions within the Citizens' Party, I unhesitatingly delved into any wrongdoing—facilitating underage girls, giving bribes, and committing espionage against rival organizations.

I was entrusted with this project, and the boundaries between good and evil were removed for success.

There were times when I was connected to yakuza and loosely organized gangsters, resorting to violent methods.

Without taking a break, I continued my challenges, and before I knew it, I had strengthened my influence within the party. At the age of thirty-six, I had one foot in the realm of power.

But from here on, to dive into the center of the political world, further achievements and sins were necessary.

A newborn arrived, just one month old.

The first time I saw my child through the glass, he was staring blankly at the ceiling, completely ignorant.

No special emotions arose—not a single one.

If anything, I was relieved that the key to moving the higher-ups had arrived.

I had been waiting for this moment for almost a year.

"Health check completed."

"Any problems?"

"There are currently no issues. There were no problems found in various tests, including the brain waves. The DNA test results also matched."

Tabuchi finished all the tests and reported the detailed results examined.

"I see."

I couldn’t afford to encounter any issues at the starting stage.

Just clearing that hurdle alone could be considered the first phase’s completion.

"You can now have direct contact if you wish."

"No need. Like the previous children, start the experiment immediately."

The White Room Project was already in its fourth phase. There was no need for wasted time.

I glanced at my child being carried away and hesitated.

Once he’s in the White Room, I won't see him for a while…

"Wait a moment."

I approached my son, who was on the other side of the separated glass.

Having him directly in front of me, I could once again feel the small life up close.

Since his neck was not yet stable, I slipped my palm under his neck and gently lifted him.

"Indeed, he’s your son, Sensei. A rigorous education awaits him, but the results will—"

"What are you talking about? Get ready for the shoot quickly."

"Uh…?"

Tabuchi, taken aback, didn’t understand my intent.

"This child is more important than my own life, and I’m sending him to the White Room. Capture the determination and tension on camera. It will be crucial promotional material for the next fundraising party."

A parent who’s indifferent about leaving their child, and a parent who reluctantly entrusts their child for the future.

It was clear which would attract more attention from the gallery.

"Uh…? Ah, yes, right."

Tabuchi hurriedly took out his phone and started capturing photos and videos of me holding the child.

After about a minute of such staging, I put the baby down.

"Take him away."

"Y-Yes, understood."

I cut my gaze from my child being taken away and started preparing for the upcoming event.

"Anyway, all the necessary preparations are now complete. Connect me to Sakayanagi."

I stepped into the world of politics about ten years ago.

On the surface, I kept sipping muddy water while smiling, but that would end today.

I would start a life for myself from here on.

I would use anything, even my own child, discard it, and reach the top.

Even someone with absolute authority, like Naoe-sensei, was no different as a stepping stone.

Eventually, I must surpass and crush this enemy.

"If you don't want to die, you better struggle on your own, Kiyotaka."

Whether a baby or an adult, in the end, you must do it alone.

You might have the worst situation, but unfortunately, mine is similar.

If you had been raised as my family, it wouldn't have just been a matter of neglect. In that sense, you could say your start was still fortunate.

In the room where my child had disappeared from, I quietly closed my eyes alone.

But life was unpredictable.

I never imagined I would have a child who would inherit my blood in any form.

The turning point came about four years after I started working under Naoe-sensei.

Yes. It was then that I learned of the existence of the White Room Project.

  1. [1]: (国会, Diet) The national legislature of Japan. Similar to the United States Congress or UK Parliament.
